      <body>
         <div type="edition" xml:lang="pra-Latn" rendition="class:83225 maturity:83209">
             <p><lb n="1"/>seṭhino <unclear>mā</unclear>tuya <space/> Isilaṇ<unclear>i</unclear>kāya <space/> seḍivay<unclear>i</unclear>kāya <space/> dāna<unclear>ṁ</unclear></p>
         </div>
         <div type="apparatus">
             <listApp>
                 <app loc="1">
                     <lem>seṭhino</lem>
                     <note>The third <foreign>akṣara</foreign> could also be read <foreign>ṇa</foreign>.</note>
                 </app>
                 <app loc="1">
                     <lem><unclear>mā</unclear>tuya</lem>
                     <note>In this cursive hand, the first <foreign>akṣara</foreign> is especially unclear, and but for the context its reading would be uncertain. On the sequence <foreign>seṭhino mātuya</foreign>, compare <bibl><ptr target="bib:Tsukamoto1996_01"/><citedRange unit="item">Sanc 111</citedRange><citedRange unit="item">Sanc 112</citedRange></bibl>.</note>
                 </app>
                 <app loc="1">
                     <lem>Isilaṇ<unclear>i</unclear>kāya</lem>
                     <note>Cf. <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00084.xml">KnI0084</ref>, ll. 1-2: Is<unclear>i</unclear>lanikāya. See also <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00294.xml">KnI0294</ref>. In both inscriptions, the donor is also characterised as <foreign>seḍivayikāya</foreign>.</note>
                 </app>
             </listApp>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" resp="part:vito">
             <p>Gift of Isilaṇṇikā from Seḍivaya, who is the mother of a guild’s chief.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
             <p>Same donor in <ref target="DHARMA_INSKnI00084.xml">KnI 84</ref>.</p>
         </div>
